{
  "doc_id": "45360",
  "text": "Sleep plays an important role in mood cognitive function. Sleep loss, sleep restriction, and sleep disorders might have a negative effect on mood and cognitive functions. Previous studies found that sleep disorders were associated with mood deficits [CITATION_1] , and sleep loss led to anger, confusion, anxiety, and depression [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . In addition, sleep loss might impair working memory [CITATION_4] and vigilant attention [CITATION_5] . Furthermore, one meta-analysis found that individuals with insomnia exhibit performance impairments in several cognitive functions, including working memory and executive functioning [CITATION_6] .",
